 x's decimal representation is greater than y's decimal representation.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: binary = \"000110\"\nOutput: \"111011\"\nExplanation: A valid transformation sequence can be:\n\"000110\" -> \"000101\" \n\"000101\" -> \"100101\" \n\"100101\" -> \"110101\" \n\"110101\" -> \"110011\" \n\"110011\" -> \"111011\"\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: binary = \"01\"\nOutput: \"01\"\nExplanation: \"01\" cannot be transformed any further.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= binary.length <= 105\nbinary consist of '0' and '1'.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maximumBinaryString(self, binary: str) -> str:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maximumBinaryString(self, binary: str) -> str:\n        # Count the number of zeros in the binary string\n        zero_count = binary.count('0')\n        \n        # If there are no zeros or only one zero, the string is already maximum\n        if zero_count <= 1:\n            return binary\n        \n        # Find the index of the first zero\n        first_zero_index = binary.index('0')\n        \n        # The result will have all ones except for one zero\n        # The zero will be at the position: first_zero_index + zero_count - 1\n        # All other positions will be ones\n        return '1' * (first_zero_index + zero_count - 1) + '0' + '1' * (len(binary) - first_zero_index - zero_count)\n```\n\nThis solution works by recognizing that the optimal strategy is to move all zeros as far to the right as possible, while converting them to ones wherever possible. The first zero in the string determines the position where the only zero in the final string will be, and all other positions will be ones.", "estimated_date": 1608422400000}